Petroleos de Venezuela S.A willannounce within two weeks the name of a foreign consortium ithas chosen to help exploit the coal deposits at Guasare inwestern Zulia state, PDVSA president Juan Chacin Guzman said.    Chacin told reporters the foreign partner will providecapital as well as technical and marketing expertise to theCarbozulia project, which the state oil company will manage.    PDVSA officials said that among those who bid for thepartnership is a consortium between Agip Carbone, a subsidiaryof Italy's Ente Nazionale Idrocarburi (ENI), and AtlanticRichfield &lt;ARC> of the United States.    Minister of Energy and Mines Arturo Hernandez Grisanti saiddiscussions are currently taking place to finalize the terms ofthe contract with the foreign partner.    PDVSA vice-president Pablo Reimpell said last week thefirst shipment of coal from the Carbozulia project should bemade during the final quarter of 1987, and would measurebetween 100-150,000 metric tons.    Plans call for production to eventually reach 500,000 mtannually. Reimpell said the original investment in the projectwill be approximately 8 billion bolivars. Reuter&#3;